<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FE66629CFD36B9E8" authority="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen, 2018" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2018" box="[425,661,1485,1508]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Illiciaceae" genus="Reyispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="parvum" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FE66629CFD36B9E8" box="[425,661,1485,1508]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Reyispermum parvum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="BBA9578AFFB8E115FD50629CFF1EBA08" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="DAF46568FFB8E115FF5F614DFBD4BFA8" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" type="description">
<paragraph id="925136E3FFB8E115FF5F614DFD45BA3F" blockId="9.[106,742,1563,1620]" box="[144,742,1563,1588]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">P l a n t F o s s i l N a m e s R e g i s t r y N u m b e r.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="925136E3FFB8E115FFA5616DFE01BA58" blockId="9.[106,742,1563,1620]" box="[106,418,1596,1620]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">PFN000094 (for new genus).</paragraph>
<paragraph id="925136E3FFB8E115FF5F613AFE61BACF" blockId="9.[106,745,1643,1731]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">
E t y m o l o g y. In recognition of Jacques Rey (*1940, â€ 2018) for his important contributions to understanding the Cretaceous geology of 
<collectingCountry id="EAF97673FFB8E115FEAF61FAFE1DBACF" box="[352,446,1707,1731]" name="Portugal" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Portugal</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="925136E3FFB8E115FF5F618AFAACBDDE" blockId="9.[106,745,1754,2100]" lastBlockId="9.[820,1459,151,466]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">D i a g n o s i s. Isolated seeds occurring singly. Seeds tiny, anatropous, bitegmic and exotestal. Seeds bilaterally symmetrical with dorsiventral plane of symmetry. Seed surface smooth without longitudinal ridges. Raphal region distinct, seen externally as a slightly raised rounded ridge that extends from the hilum to the chalazal end opposite the micropyle. Hilum and micropyle separated by a moderate zone of testal sclerenchyma. Hilar scar small, circular without a rim. Micropyle formed by the inner integument (tegmen) and marked on the seed surface by a transverse slit through the outer integument (testa) adjacent to hilar scar. Testa formed from an outer layer (exotesta) of palisade-shaped sclerenchyma cells and an inner thin layer of thin-walled parenchyma cells (mesotesta/endotesta). Testa bulging below hilum. Palisade-shaped cells of exotesta with evenly thickened anticlinal walls and a straight lumen. Anticlinal walls of exotestal cells strongly undulate toward the inside and toward the outside, resulting in stellate-undulate facets and a jigsaw puzzle-like pattern on the seed surface except in the micropylar region where the anticlinal walls are straight and the outer facets polygonal. Tegmen thin.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="925136E3FFB8E115FC9566B8FBD4BFA8" blockId="9.[820,1460,489,932]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">
C o m m e n t s o n t h e g e n u s. Seeds assigned to 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FCFB655BFC66BE2D" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2018" box="[820,965,522,545]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Illiciaceae" genus="Reyispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FCFB655BFC66BE2D" box="[820,965,522,545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Reyispermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are similar to those of 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FB0B6558FAABBE2D" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2018" box="[1220,1288,521,545]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Nymphaeaceae" genus="Pazlia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Nymphaeales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FB0B6558FAABBE2D" box="[1220,1288,521,545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Pazlia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FAF06558FA0EBE2D" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2018" box="[1343,1453,521,545]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Illiciaceae" genus="Pazliopsis" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FAF06558FA0EBE2D" box="[1343,1453,521,545]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Pazliopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but much smaller and the sclerenchyma tissue beneath the hilum is much less prominent. Seeds of 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FB38651BFA2BBE6D" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2018" box="[1271,1416,586,609]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Illiciaceae" genus="Reyispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FB38651BFA2BBE6D" box="[1271,1416,586,609]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Reyispermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are also similar in wall structure to the seeds of the extinct genus 
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FCFB65DBFC76BEAE" box="[820,981,650,674]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Illiciospermum</emphasis>
FRUMIN et E.M.FRIIS, described from the early Late Cretaceous of 
<collectingCountry id="EAF97673FFB8E115FBC865FBFB20BECE" box="[1031,1155,682,706]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="F67F4B12FFB8E115FB5D65FBFA2ABECF" author="Frumin, S. &amp; Friis, E. M." box="[1170,1417,682,707]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" pagination="265 - 288" refId="ref18050" refString="Frumin, S., Friis, E. M. (1999): Magnoliid reproductive organs from the Cenomanian-Turonian of north-western Kazakhstan: Magnoliaceae and Illiciaceae. - Plant Systematics and Evolution, 216: 265 - 288. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 01084403" type="journal article" year="1999">Frumin and Friis 1999</bibRefCitation>
), as well as seeds of extant 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FBE8659AFBD9BEEF" box="[1063,1146,715,739]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Schisandraceae" genus="Illicium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FBE8659AFBD9BEEF" box="[1063,1146,715,739]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Illicium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FB48659AFB5BBEEF" box="[1159,1272,715,739]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Illiciaceae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Illiciaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation id="F67F4B12FFB8E115FAC2659AFA0BBEEF" author="Oh, I. - C. &amp; Denk, T. &amp; Friis, E. M." box="[1293,1448,715,739]" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" pagination="175 - 209" refId="ref18316" refString="Oh, I. - C., Denk, T., Friis, E. M. (2003): Evolution of Illicium (Illiciaceae): Mapping morphological characters on the molecular tree. - Plant Systematics and Evolution, 240: 175 - 209. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 00606 - 003 - 0022 - 1" type="journal article" year="2003">Oh et al. 2003</bibRefCitation>
). The slight bulge in the hilar-micropylar area resembles the strophiole seen in 
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FC34645AFB3FBF2F" box="[1019,1180,779,803]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Illiciospermum</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FB1C645AFA85BF2F" box="[1235,1318,779,803]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Schisandraceae" genus="Illicium" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FB1C645AFA85BF2F" box="[1235,1318,779,803]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Illicium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but in these two genera the strophiole is more prominent and distinctly bulging and also clearly separates the hilum and micropyle. In 
<taxonomicName id="55EE4D60FFB8E115FC9F643CFC42BF88" authorityName="Friis &amp; Crane &amp; Pedersen" authorityYear="2018" box="[848,993,877,900]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Illiciaceae" genus="Reyispermum" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Austrobaileyales" pageId="9" pageNumber="144" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="A09AEAF1FFB8E115FC9F643CFC42BF88" box="[848,993,877,900]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="144">Reyispermum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the slight bulge in the hilar-micropylar area is positioned below the hilum.
</paragraph>
